      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/sqa-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1 is validated under 21 CFR Part 11-compliant QMS. FDA-validated solver benchmarks (NAFEMS LE1, LE10, NL1) executed and archived. DePuy Synthes internal SQA dossier covers installation qualification, operational qualification, and performance qualification for the specific solver version used. Version control via Git with signed commits; audit trail complete. Independent code review conducted by third-party assessor. SQA level 5 achieved: full traceability from requirements through test evidence with no open defects affecting QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/code-verification-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification performed using method of manufactured solutions (MMS) for the nonlinear structural solver. Convergence order confirmed at 1.97 (theoretical 2.0 for quadratic elements) across five systematically refined meshes. Patch tests passed for all element types employed (SOLID186, CONTA174, TARGE170). Round-trip verification against Abaqus 2022 for identical boundary conditions confirmed QoI agreement within 0.3%. All verification artifacts archived in controlled document management system with traceability to specific solver build."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/discretization-error-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence study performed across six refinement levels (global element size 2.0 mm to 0.25 mm) with Richardson extrapolation applied to all three QoIs. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for stiffness: 0.4%; yield force: 0.7%; force at 40 mm: 0.9%. All GCI values below 1% threshold. Production mesh (0.5 mm at screw-rod interface, 1.0 mm elsewhere) achieves asymptotic convergence range confirmed by GCI ratio test (ratio = 1.02, target 1.0). Mesh convergence dataset archived at https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-mesh-convergence-study-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/solver-error-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence monitored via force and displacement residual norms; convergence criterion set to 1e-6 (relative). Newton-Raphson iteration with line search; maximum 50 substeps with automatic bisection. Energy convergence criterion additionally applied (1e-8). Time-step sensitivity study confirmed QoI insensitivity to substep count beyond 20 substeps (difference < 0.1%). Solver log files archived for all production runs. Contact stabilization energy monitored and confirmed below 1% of total strain energy for all load increments."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/use-error-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model setup subjected to independent peer review by two senior simulation engineers not involved in original model development. Checklist-based review protocol covers geometry import fidelity, material assignment, boundary condition definition, contact pair specification, and load application. All review findings resolved and documented. Model setup script version-controlled and executed in automated pipeline to eliminate manual transcription errors. Pre-processing QA report generated automatically and archived with each simulation run. Blind replication by second analyst confirmed identical QoI outputs within floating-point precision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/model-form-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Model form assessed through systematic comparison of three constitutive model candidates: (1) linear elastic, (2) bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO), and (3) multilinear isotropic hardening (MISO) calibrated from tensile coupon data. MISO selected as production model based on lowest normalized root-mean-square error against experimental load-displacement curves (NRMSE = 2.3% vs. 8.1% for BISO and 19.4% for linear elastic). Contact formulation: augmented Lagrangian with friction coefficient 0.2 (calibrated from tribological characterization of Ti-6Al-4V on Ti-6Al-4V). Geometric nonlinearity (NLGEOM ON) confirmed necessary by comparing large- and small-deformation solutions at 40 mm displacement (8.4% difference). Model form uncertainty explicitly included in UQ budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/model-inputs-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "All model inputs characterized with quantified uncertainty distributions. Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus: 114 GPa mean, 3 GPa std (N=30 tensile coupons from same material lot). Yield strength: 880 MPa mean, 22 MPa std. Screw outer diameter: 7.5 mm nominal, tolerance band ±0.05 mm (per manufacturing drawing, confirmed by CMM measurement of N=5 specimens). Rod diameter: 5.5 mm, ±0.03 mm. Vertebral body surrogate block stiffness: characterized per ASTM F1717 Annex A1 from N=6 foam blocks per laboratory. All input distributions archived in dataset https://uofa.net/synth/data/nagaraja-material-characterization-ti6al4v. Global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices, N=10,000 quasi-random samples) identifies dominant inputs for each QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/test-samples-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: N=6, Lab 2: N=5). All specimens drawn from same production lot as clinical devices; lot traceability documented. Pre-test dimensional inspection (CMM) confirms geometric conformance to design drawing for all specimens. Material certificates of conformance (CoC) archived. Inter-laboratory variability assessed: coefficient of variation for stiffness 4.2%, yield force 3.8%, force at 40 mm 5.1%. No outliers identified by Grubbs test at alpha=0.05. Sample size justified by power analysis (beta=0.80, alpha=0.05, effect size derived from prior cannulated screw study)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/test-conditions-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted strictly per ASTM F1717-21 protocol at both laboratories. Load application rate: 5 mm/min (displacement controlled). Environmental conditions: 23 ± 2 degrees C, 50 ± 10% RH, consistent with standard ambient testing. Load cell calibration traceable to NIST; calibration certificates current for all test dates. Vertebral body surrogate foam blocks characterized per F1717 Annex A1 with stiffness values reported and included in model inputs. Fixture alignment verified by laser tracker prior to each test series. Test conditions replicated identically in FEA boundary conditions; any deviations (e.g., fixture compliance) quantified and included in uncertainty budget. Note: single loading mode (compression-bending) tested, consistent with COU scope; no additional test conditions required by the COU definition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/equivalency-inputs-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Systematic mapping performed between all experimental measurement inputs and corresponding FEA model parameters. Material properties: FEA uses distributions derived from tensile coupon tests on same material lot as test specimens. Geometry: FEA nominal geometry updated with CMM-measured dimensions for each specimen (specimen-specific models for N=11). Boundary conditions: fixture compliance measured experimentally via instrumented rigid calibration block and subtracted from raw load-displacement data; identical compliance value applied in FEA fixture model. Foam block stiffness: per-block characterization data fed directly into corresponding FEA simulation. Equivalency mapping table archived and peer-reviewed. No unresolved discrepancies between experimental and FEA input parameters."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/output-comparison-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for all three QoIs. Validation uncertainty uval computed as RSS of experimental measurement uncertainty, inter-laboratory variability, and model input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (N=10,000). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.91 (pass, threshold 1.96); yield force E/uval = 1.14 (pass); force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.62 (pass). Full load-displacement curve comparison performed using area metric (Ferson et al.); all curves within 95% prediction interval of experimental ensemble. Comparison methodology pre-specified in validation plan prior to data unblinding. Results independently verified by FDA reviewer."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/qoi-relevance-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs selected — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly specified in ASTM F1717 and are the primary outputs used in the regulatory submission to characterize mechanical performance of the pedicle screw construct. Clinical relevance: construct stiffness relates to load sharing and fusion environment; yield force represents onset of permanent deformation relevant to device integrity; force at 40 mm represents post-yield structural reserve. QoI selection documented in validation plan with traceability to device design requirements and regulatory guidance (FDA guidance on testing of spinal implants). No additional QoIs identified through hazard analysis that are not already captured."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/acceptance/validation-relevance-level5-criteria",
      "rationale": "Validation activities directly replicate the COU: same device (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), same loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), same material (Ti-6Al-4V ELI), same assembly configuration (screw-rod construct with vertebral body surrogates), same QoIs. No extrapolation beyond the validation domain required for the COU. Applicability assessment documented: validation specimens are production-equivalent devices from the same manufacturing process. The only acknowledged gap — single test condition (compression-bending only, not torsion or fatigue) — is within COU scope and does not constitute an extrapolation. Validation activity relevance confirmed by independent subject matter expert review with signed attestation archived."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw FEA model under ASTM F1717 compression-bending is accepted at MRL 5 based on the following structured evidence: (1) All 13 V&V 40 credibility factors assessed and achieved at level 5, meeting or exceeding the required level for a Medium model influence, Medium decision consequence COU at MRL 5. (2) All three pre-specified QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfy the quantitative acceptance criterion E/uval < 1.96, with maximum E/uval = 1.62 for the most challenging QoI. (3) Full uncertainty quantification via Monte Carlo (N=10,000) and global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices) demonstrate that the dominant uncertainty contributors are identified and bounded; no uncharacterized uncertainty sources remain. (4) Specimen-specific FEA models with CMM-updated geometry and per-block foam characterization eliminate systematic input equivalency gaps. (5) Independent peer review, blind replication, and FDA reviewer confirmation provide additional confidence in model setup and output comparison methodology. (6) Software quality assurance, code verification, and numerical solver error all confirmed at level 5 with full traceability. The single acknowledged limitation — testing in compression-bending mode only — is within the COU scope and does not represent an extrapolation. No weakeners identified. The model is credible for its intended use in the regulatory submission supporting the non-cannulated pedicle screw 510(k).",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
